      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, thanks for bringing this up — sharp knee pain that's been around for two weeks is definitely worth taking seriously, and I'm glad you're not just pushing through it quietly.\n\nI want to be straight with you here: **diagnosing what's going on with your knee is outside my lane as a coach.** Pain going downstairs, lasting two weeks, starting after a long run — there are several things that *could* cause that picture, and a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor is genuinely the right person to look at it. They can actually examine you, rule things out, and give you a real answer. That's not me being overly cautious — it's just the honest truth about what a coach can and can't know from a description.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically: that's a medical decision, and I'd rather you ask your doctor or pharmacist than take a coaching opinion on it. Masking pain to keep running is a road that can turn a short setback into a longer one — but how to manage that is a conversation for a clinician, not me.\n\nWhat I *can* tell you is this: **we have time.** Your race is July 11th — that's nearly 16 weeks away. If you need one, two, even three weeks to get assessed and let things settle, we absolutely have room to build you back into strong fitness before race day. Missing time now and coming back healthy is a much better path than grinding through something that gets worse. Rest right now isn't lost fitness — it's protecting the investment you've already made.\n\nOnce you've had a chance to see someone and get a clearer picture, I'd love to rework the plan around whatever they recommend.\n\n**Can you get in to see a physio or sports medicine doctor this week?** That's the single most useful next step right now — and once you have their input, we'll figure out exactly what the path forward looks like together."
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01SFb5q7DLQEbdLEGDsPkon3"
    }
  ],
